o decide whether to retry the same class or move on.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:449:Composite strategies (run a primary workflow, then refine dynamic-access coverage):\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:456:#### Running a dynamic-access strategy\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:478:For the detailed function-level notes and sequence diagram, see `docs/dynamic-access-strategy.md`.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:54:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\nforge/.codex/skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\nforge/.codex/skills/