alls that includes a line. It feels like a complex puzzle, especially considering the static nature of dynamic access here.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating dynamic access and coverage**\\n\\nI’m wondering if invoking `authenticate` might trigger Groovy call sites, which could lead to class$ access. But it looks like there's no `Class.forName` in `authenticate`, and CertAuthScheme.class$ is the only dynamic access point. It feels challenging to see how tests can improve this situation.\\n\\nMaybe I could use GroovyShell to invoke a static method, although the coverage tool might not interact as expected. Adding Groovy dispatch with `InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod` could be risky, but I should try. I need to guard against errors like `NoClassDefFoundError`, especially if Groovy hasn't initialized the class. It's a bit complex, but it’s about validating fallbacks while ensuring no coverage line remains null.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering runtime trace coverage**\\n\\nI’m pondering whether the workflow might identify “newly covered” lines through runtime tracing, but that doesn’t seem likely. It feels like I might need to integrate `InvokerHelper` along with a catch mechanism. This could help in managing potential errors while attempting to establish better coverage, even if it’s through a different approach. I want to ensure I’m making progress without disregarding any important coverage details or error handling along the way.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_idJcNJpNYZf0hpJcPBIA7Clh|fc_0cea330babe0ccb8016a0079dfb9b4819fb9be3cd29bed3382", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"class NativeImageSupport\" -n tests src buildSrc ~/.gradle/caches 2>/dev/null | head -20"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1884, "output": 1082, "cacheRead": 52736, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 55702, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0